I've only just noticed from reading more bedtime stories to my child recently that writers often use "toward" and "towards" interchangeably as in "the princess ran toward(s) the dragon" and my dumb brain tries to always read it as "towards" but are there grammar rules for this??
@Jet_Blakk Makes sense but interesting that I've seen both in the same bedtime story
@cathieshooter Oh this looks like a great read. Thank you!
Well that explains it! — thanks for the link @cathieshooter  https://t.co/4BSB9oO3EQ

TL;DR towards is nowadays more common in UK English and toward is more common in US English, but the history and etymology along with adjective, adverb, and noun usage (read the article) is a bit more nuanced, so pretty much just use whichever one sounds better to you ¯\_ (ツ)_/¯
